definition.value: quantification of the effect of persistent interference in daily life activities and role performance by psychiatric conditions or related symptoms, usually established through a combination of medical assessments and questionnaires
quantification of the level of joint damage, eg through radiological analysis
one of the primary characteristics of asthma, characterised by easily triggered increased airway smooth muscle contractility
quantification of the protease inhibitor alpha-1-antitrypsin in the blood.  The test is used in the diagnosis of early onset emphysema and liver disease.
A soluble ST2 measurement is the quantification of the ST2 protein, also known as Interleukin-1 receptor-like 1 or IL1RL1. The protein  ST2 levels are associated with adverse cardiovascular events.
response to treatment with an inhibitor of mTOR (mammalian Target Of Rapamycin), such as everolimus or rapamycin
quantification of symmetric or asymmetric dimethylarginine in the blood

quantificiation of ability to detect sharp boundaries (stimuli) and to detect slight changes in luminance at regions without distinct contours. Psychophysical measurements of this visual function are used to evaluate visual acuity and to detect eye disease.
quantification of the volume of grey matter in the brain, usuallly through an MRI scan. Grey matter volume is associated with schizophrenia.

quantification of the amino acid derivate homoarginine in the blood. Low levels are associated with cardiovascular disease risk and for stroke in patients undergoing coronoary angiograpahy and decreased kidney function

The gradual irreversible changes in structure of skin that occur as a result of the passage of time.. In humans, skin aging can be precipitated as a result of weather and sun exposure, and expresses through the appearance of wrinkles and localised changes in skin pigmentation

value.value: A scoliosis with no known cause arising in adolescent.

A learning disorder characterized by an impairment in processing written words. Reading difficulties can include distortions, omissions or substitutions of characters. Oral and silent reading difficulties can include faulty and slow comprehension.

definition.value: A communication disorder that involves the processing of linguistic information.
Symptom associated with autism spectrum disorder such as impairment in verbal and nonverbal communication, social interactions, and/or imaginative play.

Significant problems using verbal and nonverbal communication for social purposes, leading to impairments in their ability to effectively communicate, participate socially, maintain social relationships, or otherwise perform academically or occupationally.

Symptom associated with borderline personality disorder such as unstable self-image and mood together with volatile interpersonal relationships, self-damaging impulsivity, recurrent suicidal threats or gestures and/or self-mutilating behavior
The consumption of illegal drug such as heroine. Note that some drug like cannabis are illegal in some countries but legal in others.
A disinhibited behaviour non-substance related as opposed to disinhibited behaviour due to alcohol consumption for example.

An array design in which a reporter on an array associated with a BioSequence that has a context dependent predicted signal. e.g. a yeast reporter on a human array, is a control biosequence expected to be of low signal if no spikes are used. If spikes are used, the signal is expected to be high.
An array design in which an array contains a reporter where only buffer was deposited on the array, acting as a control.
An array design in which a reporter on an array has no material or buffer was deposited on the array.
An array design in which a reporter has genomic DNA deposited on it; the genomic DNA may be fragmented, e.g. salmon sperm DNA, Cot1DNA.

An array design in which a reporter is included that could be used to determine the quality and general performance of the labeled extract. An example is a pool of BioSequences representing widely-expressed genes (i.e., housekeeping genes).
An array design in which a reporter is used as a control where some label has been deposited. This includes fluor and radioactively labeled oligos and fluors alone.
An array design in which a Reporter is included on an array of whose BioSequence is of known length used as a methodological control for hybridization efficiency.
An array design in which a reporter is used a control for reasons such as quality or result verifcation.
A cell line derived from human prostate carcinoma. The patient was a 69-year-old male, and the sample was derived from brain metastasis.

PEO1 is an adherent cell line derived from a malignant effusion from the peritoneal ascites of a patient with a poorly differentiated serous adenocarcinoma. The patient previously received cisplatin, 5-fluorouracil and chlorambucil treatment. PEO1 is tumourigenic in immunologically-deprived CBA mice. PEO1 exhibits good growth in semi-solid medium (agar). PEO1 is from the same patient as the PEO4 and PEO6 cell lines (Sigma Catalogue numbers 10032309 & 10032310).This cell line is one of nine from the PE ovarian adenocarcinoma panel (derived from 4 patients at varying stages of ovarian cancer, isolated from various malignant sites, and at various treatment stages) available at ECACC which provides a model system for research into the mechanism of oestrogen action on ovarian adenocarcinoma tumour cells, and for the study of efficacy and toxicity of oestrogen protagonists. (Sigma-Aldrich catalog number 10032308)
